PHYTOPLASMA DISEASE, COCONUT PALM - SRI LANKA
*********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: Wed 20 Feb 2008
Source: Lanka Business Online [edited]
<http://www.lankabusinessonline.com/fullstory.php?newsID=1513892127&no_view=1&SEARCH_TERM=14>


A bacterium spreading a lethal yellowing disease on coconut palms has
entered Sri Lanka threatening more than 200 000 trees on the southern coast
of the island, coconut experts say. The bacteria known as "phytoplasma"
came through a shipment of ornamental palms that were not quarantined
before entering the island, Salinda Dissanayake, minister of coconut
development and nation building says. The disease turns the leaves yellow
and causes most of the fruits to drop prematurely. The whole crown of the
palm also falls, leaving a bare trunk, experts from the coconut research
institute said.

As a preventive measure, the institute has declared a 3 km (2 mi) wide
buffer zone along the coastal line in the south, ranging from Weligama, 140
km (87 mi) south of Colombo, to Matara, which is situated a further 20 km
(12 mi) away. "We hope the bacteria will not be able to cross over 3
kilometers," C Jayasekara, director, coconut research institute, told
reporters. The coconut trees that were infected within the buffer zone had
been burnt to prevent the spreading of the bacteria.

The research institute has started conducting experiments to find a
solution and ensure the disease does not spread to other crops. It has
restricted items made from coconut and coconut plants being transported out
of the infected southern region, in a bid to contain the disease.
Meanwhile, Dissanayake says a Non Governmental Organization has transported
around 10 000 coconut plants to the eastern region for cultivation. "We
cannot order the police to seize such plant loads since there are no legal
provisions for that." The disease can affect the industry if it spreads all
over the island, he said.

Sri Lanka's coconut cultivations are mainly in the north western province
of Kurunegala and Puttalam. This area is called the 'coconut triangle'. In
2002, around 443 000 acres (179 300 hectares) or 45 per cent of the total
coconut acreage, were found in the north western districts. In the southern
region, coconut acreage was around 117 000 acres (47 350 hectares) which
was around 12 per cent of the total.

